# TypeScript Standards

## Type Definitions

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Use interfaces for object shapes
interface FlashCard {
  id: string;
  question: string;
  answer: string;
  difficulty: 'easy' | 'medium' | 'hard';
  createdAt: Date;
}

// ✅ GOOD - Use type for unions and primitives
type CardStatus = 'active' | 'archived' | 'draft';
type CardId = string;
```

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Silent catch
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (e) {}

// ✅ GOOD - Proper error handling
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Failed to fetch data:', error);
  throw new Error('Unable to retrieve data', { cause: error });
}
```

## Function Types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Explicit return types for exported functions
export async function createCard(data: CardData): Promise<FlashCard> {
  return await api.post('/cards', data);
}

// ✅ GOOD - Use const assertions for readonly data
const DIFFICULTY_LEVELS = ['easy', 'medium', 'hard'] as const;
type Difficulty = typeof DIFFICULTY_LEVELS[number];
```

## Strict Mode

- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.json
- Use `satisfies` operator for type checking
- Prefer `unknown` over `any`
- Use optional chaining `?.` and nullish coalescing `??`

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const config = {
  apiUrl: 'https://api.example.com',
  timeout: 5000,
} satisfies Config;

const value = data?.user?.name ?? 'Unknown';
```